			<h1><span class="less"><a href="index.html">SLE 2015</a> paper:</span><br><i>The whiley rewrite language (WyRL)</i></h1>
			<h2><a href="../profile/DavidJPearce.html">David J. Pearce</a></h2>
<ul><li>DOI: <a href="https://doi.org/10.1145/2814251.2814266">10.1145/2814251.2814266</a></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t3b.html"><span class="tagM">T3B: Transformation Languages</span></a><ul><li> WyRL is explicitly a rewrite/transformation language for specifying declarative rewrite rules.
</li></ul></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t4c.html"><span class="tagL">T4C: Vertical Transformation</span></a><ul><li> It includes a code generator that produces executable components from rewrite specifications.
</li></ul></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t4a.html"><span class="tagL">T4A: Workbenches</span></a><ul><li> It is delivered as a standalone tool, i.e., language engineering infrastructure around the rewrite language.
</li></ul></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t5d.html"><span class="tagL">T5D: Formal Methods</span></a><ul><li> Rewrite systems and their generators are typically justified with formal properties/correctness arguments.
</li></ul></li></ul>
